      "text": "6. SELF JOIN",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "6. SELF JOIN",
      "autoResize": true,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
    {
      "id": "d7cMQ1P7Xt6IirJavqQoy",
      "type": "text",
      "x": -16251.466544818788,
      "y": 20458.73438262003,
      "width": 1741.9995117187502,
      "height": 720,
      "angle": 0,
      "strokeColor": "#1e1e1e",
      "backgroundColor": "transparent",
      "fillStyle": "solid",
      "strokeWidth": 4,
      "strokeStyle": "solid",
      "roughness": 1,
      "opacity": 100,
      "groupIds": [],
      "frameId": null,
      "index": "bM3",
      "roundness": null,
      "seed": 820741699,
      "version": 242,
      "versionNonce": 21556589,
      "isDeleted": false,
      "boundElements": [],
      "updated": 1775373758123,
      "link": null,
      "locked": false,
      "text": "A self join is a type of join in which a table is joined to itself. This is useful when\nyou need to compare rows within the same table, such as relating employees to their\nmanagers in an organizational hierarchy.\n\nConsider an employees table that needs to represent employees and their managers. To\nachieve this, we can introduce a new column called manager_id in the employees table to\nstore the ID of each employee's manager. After updating the table, we'll perform a self\njoin to associate each employee with their manager.\n\nStep 1: Altering the Table to Add the manager_id Column\nALTER TABLE employees ADD COLUMN manager_id INT;\n\nStep 2: Updating the Table with Manager Information\nUPDATE employees SET manager_id = 3 WHERE employee_id = 1;\nUPDATE employees SET manager_id = 3 WHERE employee_id = 2;\nUPDATE employees SET manager_id = 4 WHERE employee_id = 3;",
      "fontSize": 36,
      "fontFamily": 8,
      "textAlign": "left",
      "verticalAlign": "top",
      "containerId": null,
      "originalText": "A self join is a type of join in which a table is joined to itself. This is useful when you need to compare rows within the same table, such as relating employees to their managers in an organizational hierarchy.\n\nConsider an employees table that needs to represent employees and their managers. To achieve this, we can introduce a new column called manager_id in the employees table to store the ID of each employee's manager. After updating the table, we'll perform a self join to associate each employee with their manager.\n\nStep 1: Altering the Table to Add the manager_id Column\nALTER TABLE employees ADD COLUMN manager_id INT;\n\nStep 2: Updating the Table with Manager Information\nUPDATE employees SET manager_id = 3 WHERE employee_id = 1;\nUPDATE employees SET manager_id = 3 WHERE employee_id = 2;\nUPDATE employees SET manager_id = 4 WHERE employee_id = 3;",
      "autoResize": false,
      "lineHeight": 1.25
    },
